  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good books about time management?",
  "response": "Here are some highly recommended books on time management, productivity, and efficiency:\n\n1. **\"Getting Things Done: The Art of Stress-Free Productivity\" by David Allen**  \n   A classic in the field, this book introduces the GTD method, a system for organizing tasks and reducing stress by breaking down overwhelming projects into manageable steps.\n\n2. **\"The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People\" by Stephen R. Covey**  \n   This book focuses on principles of personal and professional effectiveness, including time management, prioritization, and goal setting.\n\n3. **\"Eat That Frog!: 21 Great Ways to Stop Procrastinating and Get More Done in Less Time\" by Brian Tracy**  \n   Based on the idea of tackling your most challenging task first (your \"frog\"), this book offers practical strategies to overcome procrastination and improve productivity.\n\n4. **\"Deep Work: Rules for Focused Success in a Distracted World\" by Cal Newport**  \n   This book emphasizes the importance of focused, uninterrupted work and provides strategies for eliminating distractions and achieving peak productivity.\n\n5. **\"The Power of Habit: Why We Do What We Do in Life and Business\" by Charles Duhigg**  \n   While not purely about time management, this book explores how habits shape our lives and offers insights into building productive routines.\n\n6. **\"Make Time: How to Focus on What Matters Every Day\" by Jake Knapp and John Zeratsky**  \n   Written by two former Google employees, this book provides simple, actionable strategies for prioritizing what truly matters and creating more meaningful days.\n\n7. **\"Atomic Habits: An Easy & Proven Way to Build Good Habits & Break Bad Ones\" by James Clear**  \n   This book focuses on the power of small, incremental changes to build habits that improve productivity and time management over time.\n\n8. **\"Manage Your Day-to-Day: Build Your Routine, Find Your Focus, and Sharpen Your Creative Mind\" by Jocelyn K. Glei**  \n   This book offers advice from creative professionals on how to streamline your daily routine, stay focused, and maximize productivity.\n\n9. **\"The One Thing: The Surprisingly Simple Truth Behind Extraordinary Results\" by Gary Keller and Jay Papasan**  \n   This book advocates for focusing on one critical task at a time and explains how this approach can lead to greater success and efficiency.\n\n10. **\"168 Hours: You Have More Time Than You Think\" by Laura Vanderkam**  \n    This book challenges the notion of time scarcity and offers practical tips for making the most of the 168 hours in a week.\n\nEach of these books offers unique perspectives and strategies, so you can choose one that aligns with your specific needs and challenges.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
